liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy says Ukrainian forces have lost no positions in their counter-offensive against Russian troops, while enemy forces have sustained only losses. "In some sectors, our forces are moving forward, in others they are defending positions or resisting assaults and intensified attacks from the occupiers," Zelenskyy says. "We have no lost positions, only liberated ones. And they have only losses. Overall, the situation is one of pressure, from us, which paves the way for our flag." Ukraine's Deputy Defence Minister Hanna Maliar says the "biggest blow" in Ukraine's military campaign is yet to come, but admits the operation is difficult as Russia throws all it can to stop the offensive. "The enemy will not easily give up their positions, and we must prepare ourselves for a tough duel. In fact, that is what is happening right now," Maliar says. Meanwhile, Zelenskyy has also praised Britain's decision to maintain its sanctions against Russia.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Zelenskyy claims Ukraine hasn't lost any positions in recent counter-offensive

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The United States and Canada are deploying air and sea resources in a joint effort to locate the missing submersible on a tourism expedition to explore the wreckage of the Titanic. Rear Admiral John Mauger says the search is challenging due to the remoteness of the location, and water depth of around 4,000 metres. He says both the US and Canadian Coast Guards are using visual and radar searches "to locate the craft and rescue the people on board". Organisers OceanGate Expeditions says in a statement that it is "mobilising all options" to rescue those on the underwater vessel, which has five people on board.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: US and Canada deploy more vessels as search continues for missing Titanic submersible

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: UK politicians have voted to approve a report that Boris Johnson misled parliament over parties held during the COVID pandemic. The House of Commons voted by 354 to seven to endorse the report, which recommends sanctioning the former prime minister. He will have his parliamentary pass revoked and — had he not already quit — he would have faced a 90-day suspension from parliament. Johnson abruptly resigned from parliament 10 days ago, after seeing an advance copy of the report, calling the inquiry a "witch hunt".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: UK MPs vote on Boris Johnson partygate report

children.content: (Reuters: Peter Nicholls/File Photo)

He will have his
parliamentary pass revoked
and — had he not already quit — he would have faced a 90-day suspension from parliament.
Johnson abruptly resigned from parliament 10 days ago, after seeing an advance copy of the report, calling the inquiry a "witch hunt".
